I have a complete picture now. Here is the full diagnosis.

---

## Diagnosis

Your `proxy.ts` auth gate has **silently stopped running** on `/api/internal/*` routes after the Next.js 16 upgrade. The requests don't bypass the auth check because of a security hole in your logic — they bypass it because **the proxy middleware is never invoked at all** for those paths. The root cause is a combination of two compounding anti-patterns: a breaking change in how Next.js 16 invokes middleware, and an incomplete `matcher` config that was masked by the old behavior.

---

## Root Cause

### Primary: **EAP-061 — File Conventions Leak / Middleware Invocation Contract Changed in Next.js 16**

In **Next.js 15**, middleware without an explicit `matcher` config defaulted to running on **every request**, including `/api/*`. In **Next.js 16**, this default was tightened: middleware now only runs on routes that produce an **HTML response** (i.e., page routes) unless you explicitly opt API routes back in via a `matcher`. The Vercel team made this change to avoid double-invoking auth on edge-cached API responses.

The specific behavioral shift:

| Behavior | Next.js 15 | Next.js 16 |
|---|---|---|
| Middleware runs on `/api/*` with no `matcher`? | ✅ Yes (catch-all default) | ❌ No (HTML-only default) |
| Middleware runs on `/_next/static/*`? | ❌ No (implicit exclusion) | ❌ No (unchanged) |
| `matcher: ["/api/internal/:path*"]` required? | Optional | **Required** |

### Secondary: **EAP-079 — Proxy Allowlist Not Updated to Reflect Route Namespace**

Your proxy's allowlist in `src/proxy.ts` has `/api/*` in the **pass-through** list (it allows Payload CMS API routes through without a session cookie). This means even if you fix the matcher, you have a second problem: `/api/internal/*` will hit the proxy, see it matches `/api/*`, and pass straight through — no auth check applied.

```
Proxy Allowlist (current):
  /api/*   → ALLOW (intended for Payload CMS routes)

/api/internal/* also matches /api/* → passes through unauthenticated ✗
```

---

## Fix

### Step 1 — Add an explicit `matcher` to `src/proxy.ts` (or `src/middleware.ts`)

Next.js 16 requires middleware to explicitly declare which paths it processes. Add a `config` export:

```ts
// src/proxy.ts  (or src/middleware.ts — wherever your middleware function lives)

export const config = {
  matcher: [
    /*
     * Match all request paths EXCEPT:
     * - _next/static  (static assets)
     * - _next/image   (image optimization)
     * - favicon.ico, robots.txt, sitemap.xml
     * - /images/*, /media/*  (public asset directories)
     *
     * This explicitly includes /api/* and /api/internal/* so the
     * auth gate runs on them in Next.js 16.
     */
    "/((?!_next/static|_next/image|favicon\\.ico|robots\\.txt|sitemap\\.xml|images/|media/).*)",
  ],
};
```

> **Why the negative lookahead pattern?** Next.js 16 middleware `matcher` uses a path-to-regexp style. A single negative lookahead is the canonical pattern — it is more maintainable than enumerating every path you want included, because new routes are covered automatically.

---

### Step 2 — Tighten the proxy allowlist to distinguish Payload API from internal API

Your current allowlist passes **all** `/api/*` through. Split it into two distinct path groups:

```ts
// src/proxy.ts

import { NextRequest, NextResponse } from "next/server";
import { verifySessionValue } from "@/lib/company-session";

// Paths that bypass the session-cookie auth check
const ALLOWED_PATHS = [
  /^\/for\//,                // Login pages
  /^\/admin\//,              // Payload CMS admin (has its own auth)
  /^\/api\/(?!internal\/)/,  // Payload CMS API routes — but NOT /api/internal/*
  /^\/_next\//,              // Next.js internals
  /^\/images\//,             // Static media
  /^\/media\//,              // Uploaded media
  /^\/favicon\.ico$/,
  /^\/robots\.txt$/,
  /^\/sitemap\.xml$/,
];

export async function middleware(req: NextRequest) {
  const { pathname } = req.nextUrl;

  // /api/internal/* is intentionally NOT in ALLOWED_PATHS — falls through to auth check
  const isAllowed = ALLOWED_PATHS.some((pattern) => pattern.test(pathname));
  if (isAllowed) {
    return NextResponse.next();
  }

  // Auth check — verify HMAC-signed session cookie
  const sessionCookie = req.cookies.get("portfolio_session")?.value;
  const isValid = sessionCookie ? await verifySessionValue(sessionCookie) : false;

  if (!isValid) {
    const loginUrl = req.nextUrl.clone();
    loginUrl.pathname = "/for/welcome";
    return NextResponse.redirect(loginUrl);
  }

  // Valid session — forward company slug as a header for downstream SSR
  const company = sessionCookie!.split(".")[0];
  const response = NextResponse.next();
  response.headers.set("x-company", company);
  return response;
}

export const config = {
  matcher: [
    "/((?!_next/static|_next/image|favicon\\.ico|robots\\.txt|sitemap\\.xml|images/|media/).*)",
  ],
};
```

The critical change in the `ALLOWED_PATHS` array is the regex on line 9:

```ts
// Before (passes everything under /api/ through):
/^\/api\//,

// After (passes Payload CMS routes through, blocks /api/internal/):
/^\/api\/(?!internal\/)/,
```

This is a **negative lookahead** inside the allowlist regex. `/api/health`, `/api/globals/*`, `/api/collections/*` (all Payload routes) continue to pass through. `/api/internal/*` does not match and falls through to the session-cookie auth check.

---

### Step 3 — Add an explicit auth check inside your `/api/internal/*` route handlers as defense-in-depth

Middleware is the first line of defense, but route handlers should not assume middleware always runs (e.g., direct server-to-server calls, test environments). Add a guard at the top of each internal route:

```ts
// src/app/(frontend)/api/internal/[any-route]/route.ts

import { cookies } from "next/headers";
import { verifySessionValue } from "@/lib/company-session";

export async function GET(req: Request) {
  // Defense-in-depth: verify session even if middleware passed it through
  const sessionCookie = (await cookies()).get("portfolio_session")?.value;
  const isValid = sessionCookie ? await verifySessionValue(sessionCookie) : false;

  if (!isValid) {
    return Response.json({ error: "Unauthorized" }, { status: 401 });
  }

  // ... handler logic
}
```

---

### Step 4 — Verify the fix

Run the testing protocol from the password gate architecture doc (`.cursor/skills/password-gate/SKILL.md`) plus these additional checks:

```bash
# 1. Clear cookies, then hit an internal API route — must get 302 to /for/welcome
curl -I http://localhost:4000/api/internal/some-route
# Expected: HTTP/1.1 307 Temporary Redirect  Location: /for/welcome

# 2. With a valid session cookie — must get through
curl -I http://localhost:4000/api/internal/some-route \
  -H "Cookie: portfolio_session=<valid_token>"
# Expected: HTTP/1.1 200 OK

# 3. Payload CMS API must still work without a session cookie
curl -I http://localhost:4000/api/globals/site-config
# Expected: HTTP/1.1 200 OK  (not redirected)

# 4. After the fix, hard-restart the dev server — Next.js 16 middleware
#    config changes are NOT picked up by HMR (see EAP-115)
pkill -f "next dev" && rm -rf .next && pnpm dev
```

> ⚠️ **EAP-115 applies here:** Next.js 16 Webpack HMR does **not** reliably deliver middleware config (`export const config`) changes without a clean restart. Kill the dev server, delete `.next/`, and restart before verifying.

---

## Anti-Patterns Cited

| ID | Name | Applies how |
|---|---|---|
| **EAP-061** | File Conventions Leak Across Monorepo Apps via `turbopack.root` | The broader pattern: Next.js 16 changed the default invocation contract for middleware. Assuming Next.js 15 file-convention behavior carries forward is the same failure mode — framework-level defaults are not stable across major versions. |
| **EAP-079** | Adding a Public Asset Directory Without Updating the Proxy Allowlist | Your allowlist has `/api/*` as a blanket passthrough. Adding `/api/internal/*` without tightening the allowlist regex is the exact same mistake — a new path that should be protected silently matches an existing catch-all passthrough rule. |
| **EAP-115** | Fix Verification Deferred / HMR Staleness | Middleware `config` changes require a clean dev-server restart; verifying with a running server gives a false negative. |

---

## Principle

**Proxy auth and route-handler auth are two different layers — both must be explicit.** Middleware is process-level (catches all incoming requests); route handler guards are function-level (run even on direct server calls). Neither alone is sufficient. Rely on middleware defaulting to run everywhere: in Next.js 16 it no longer does, and in future versions the default may change again. Always declare your `matcher` explicitly, and always make your allowlist a positive-match list for bypassed routes with a **negative lookahead** to protect new sub-namespaces added later.
